@node "intro" "Introduction"

  Welcome to the AmigaGuide documentation for @{b}FileGizmo.@{ub}

  @{b}FileGizmo@{ub} is a program that creates an AppIcon on the workbench screen.
  When the user drops an icon on the appicon a list of actions apropriate to
  that type of file appears. The user then selects which actions to use on
  the file.

  Pretty simple huh?
@endnode

@node "features" "features"

    @{b}FileGizmo@{ub} has the following features

      - It's a commodity.

      - Choose icon, icon position and config file in tooltypes.

      - Easy to use gadtools GUI for configuration.

      - Can be configured for over 500 different file types and
        over 1000 different possible actions.

      - Option to open an output window for commands

      - Written in Blitz Basic II in about a week.

      - Ummm...not much else really....
@endnode

@node "requirements" "Requirements"

  @{b}FileGizmo@{ub} has the following requrements:

      - An Amiga (Are we sick of this joke yet?).

      - OS2.x+ (I think. I have OS3.0 and so do most people I know).

      - A little bit of disk space.

      - Some files to drop on it or it will feel unloved.
@endnode

@node "install" "Installing FileGizmo"

  @{b}FileGizmo@{ub} is pretty easy to install.

  You can either

      - Double click on the install icon

      - Or copy the files to where you want them.

  If the @{b}FileGizmo@{ub} executable is in a different drawer to the config file you
  should put the full path and name of the config file in the CONFIG tooltype.
@endnode

@node "usage" "How To Use FileGizmo"

  @{b}FileGizmo@{ub} is fairly simple to use.

  Just drop icons on it.

  But first you will need to @{"Configure" link "configure" 0} it for your system.
  To open the Configuration window double click on the FileGizmo appicon.
  When the window is open pressing the right mouse button will let you access
  the @{"Project" link "cf_menu" 0} menu.
@endnode

@node "configure" "Configuring File Gizmo"

  If you double click on the @{b}FileGizmo@{ub} appicon the configuration window will
  appear.

  There are two lists in the configuration window. On the left is the
  @{"File Types" link "cf_filetypes" 0} list and on the right is the @{"Actions" link "cf_actions" 0} list. Beneath each
  list are a number of gadgets.

  Beneath the File Types list is a @{"Name" link "cf_ft_name" 0} text entry gadget, an @{"Extension" link "cf_ft_extension" 0} text
  entry box, a @{"New" link "cf_ft_new" 0} button and a @{"Delete" link "cf_ft_delete" 0} button.

  Beneath the Actions list is a @{"Name" link "cf_act_name" 0} text entry gadget, a @{"Command" link "cf_act_command" 0} text entry
  gadget, an @{"Open CLI Window" link "cf_act_cli" 0} checkbox, a @{"New" link "cf_act_new" 0} button and a @{"Delete" link "cf_act_delete" 0} Button.

  At the bottom of the window are the @{"Save" link "cf_save" 0}, @{"Quit" link "cf_quit" 0}, @{"Cancel" link "cf_cancel" 0} and @{"Use" link "cf_use" 0} buttons.

  To create a new File Type, click on the New button beneath the File Types
  list. Select the new entry in the File Types list. Change the name in the
  Name gadget and enter the file extensions for that file type in the
  Extension gadget.

  File Extensions should begin with a dot (".") and be separated with
  semi-colons (";"). There should not be any spaces.

  To create a new Action, click on the New button beneath the Actions list.
  Select the new entry in the Actions list. Change the name of the action in
  the Name gadget and enter the command for the action in the Command gadget.
  If you want an output window opened for the command place a check in the
  Open CLI Window gadget.

  To delete a File Type or Action you should select the name in the
  apropriate list then click on the Delete button beneath that list.

  Certain aspects of @{b}FileGizmo@{ub} can also be configured with @{"ToolTypes." link "cf_tooltypes" 0}
@endnode

@node "cf_filetypes" "File Types List"

  This is a list of all available File Types. File Types are recognised by
  their extension (usually a dot followed by about three letters...
  eg .jpg for a jpeg picture). Select a name in the list to edit a File Type.

  One item in the File Type list is not really a File Type. It is the
  @{"DEFAULT File Type" link "cf_default" 0}.
@endnode

@node "cf_actions" "Actions List"

  Actions are the commands that are performed on a file that has been dropped
  on the FileGizmo appicon. To edit an action select it's name from the
  Actions list.

  To associate an action with a file double click on it's name in the
  list. An asterisk ("*") will appear next to the name. All Actions with
  asterisks next to thier names are associated with the currently selected
  File Type.
@endnode

@node "cf_ft_name" "Name"

  This is the name of the currently selected File Type.
@endnode

@node "cf_ft_extension" "Extensions"

  This is a list of the possible file extensions of the currently slelected
  File Type.
@endnode

@node "cf_ft_new" "New Filetype"

  This button creates a new File Type called (strangley enough) "!NEW!".
@endnode

@node "cf_ft_delete" "Deleting File Types"

  This button deletes the currently selected File Type.
@endnode

@node "cf_act_name" "Name"

  This is the name of the currently selected Action.
@endnode

@node "cf_act_command" "Command"

  This is the command to be executed by the currently selected action.

  You must specify the full path to the program to execute
  (eg. "System:Utilities/Multiview" or "c:more" ).

  There are a number of tokens you can include in the command line that will
  be replaced with other strings before the command is executed :


      - %f Will be replaced with the full path and file name of the icon
           dropped on the @{b}FileGizmo@{ub} appicon.

      - %F Will be replaced by the file name of the icon only.

      - %D Will be replaced by the path of the icon only.


  It is a good idea to put quotes around the token otherwise you will get
  errors when you try to use @{b}FileGizmo@{ub} with filenames that contain spaces.

  eg. The following command will extract an LHA archive to the drawer the
      icon is located in:

      c:lha x "%f" -w "%D"

      If the lha file you dropped on FileGizmo was Ram Disk:FileGizmo2.lha
      the following command would then be executed:

      c:lha x "Ram Disk:FileGizmo2.lha" -w "Ram Disk:"

      If there had not been quotes around the tokens the space in the name
      Ram Disk: would have caused an error.
@endnode

